Introduction

In todayâ€™s sharp -transit financial markets -with heavy uncertainty around geopolitics, understanding and estimating stock behaviour has never been more important for investors, traders and analysts. This study examines NVIDIA (NVDA) time series dynamics by looking at its adjusted stock prices, instability and trading volumes. We both use new forecasting approaches (Prophet models of meta) and traditional statistical methods such as linear regression and STL decomposition. With the integration of these methods, we not only want to estimate future trends, but also break the time series into its main components: trends, seasonal and residual.

Data and Methodology

Data Acquisition

We are using Yahoo Finance to collect historical data on Nvidia for this project. The dataset covers the duration from January 1, 2015 to the present, and includes the daily adjusted closing price and trading volumes. We calculated the daily log returns and used a 30-day rolling window to estimate volatility. These measurements form the basis for our analysis.

Forecasting with Prophet

The Prophet is a powerful forecast tool that identifies the effects of patterns, seasonal and holiday in time chain data. In our investigation, we created a series of Prophet models for daily and monthly data.

  • Daily Forecasts:
    We used the Prophet to predict the daily instability and trade volume of NVDA stock. Estimates include a shaded confidence interval, showing the degree of uncertainty in our estimates. In addition, linear regression trends are overlay on historical data, acting as a base line to validate the Prophetâ€™s forecasts.

  • Monthly Forecasts:
    Monthly forecast: To reduce noise, we collected daily data up to a monthly level. This method shows long -term seasonal trends when lubricating short -term swings, which can be easy to interpret. Both average monthly instability and total monthly trade volume are modeling and anticipated with the Prophet.

Classical Methods: Linear Regression and STL Decomposition

In addition to the Prophet, we used linear regression on all charts to provide a spontaneous view of longer trends. The linear regression provides a simple base line to compare against more sophisticated estimates of the Prophet.

We also used STL (with seasonal-trend decomposition) on the monthly set. The STL decomposition divides the time chain into three components:

  • Trend: The long-term movement.
  • Seasonal: The repeating periodic fluctuations.
  • Residual: The noise or irregular variation.

Additionally we calculated the seasonal dimension (difference between maximum and minimum values of the seasonal component) to assess the importance of seasonal variations in our data.

Seasonal Decomposition

STL decomposition is used to divide the time chain on menstrual data, seasonal and residual components collected.

The trend component manifests the underlying long -term movement.

Seasonal component: displays repeated patterns in a one -year cycle. Seasonal dimensions (difference between maximum and minimum) measures the magnitude of these seasonal changes.

The residual component catch random noise that is not explained by trend or seasonal.

The decomposition of monthly average instability displays the cyclical character of the uncertainty of the market, while the breakdown of the monthly trading volume shows seasonal ups and downs in behaviour - it is very useful for NVDA because the stock is so unstable.

Seasonal dimensions (the difference between the maximum and minimum of the seasonal component) determines how large the seasonal variations are. It provides insight into the importance of seasonal in the market behavior of Nvidia.

Conclusion

This time series project combines modern methods with traditional statistical analysis to provide a comprehensive approach to the market performance of Nvidia. The combination of Prophet forecasts, linear regression trends and STL decomposition provides a multi -faceted view of daily and monthly dynamics.
